{"status":"success","result":"Fair point, I'll be straight.\n\nIt's *decent* for a first pass, but there are real issues:\n\n*The regex routing is fragile.* `CODING_PATTERN` is 400+ characters trying to guess intent from keywords. \"read the book\" could match because \"read\" + \"script\" somewhere nearby. It'll misfire and you'll never know why until Jarvis does something weird.\n\n*The auto-escalation pattern is also regex on failure text.* So if the model just happens to say \"I'm sorry to hear that\" in the wrong context, it escalates unnecessarily. And if a model fails silently — gives a confidently wrong answer without apologizing — it never escalates at all. That's the worse case.\n\n*`shouldThink()` has the same problem.* \"sure\" and \"try\" are in the THINK_PATTERN. Those are incredibly common words. Someone saying \"sure, sounds good\" is going to trigger thinking mode.\n\n*The escalation ladder is sound in concept* but it's entirely self-reported — the model decides when it needs help. Models are notoriously bad at knowing what they don't know. The system trusts Jarvis to judge his own competence, which is a weak link.\n\n*What's actually good:*\n• The `ollama_generate` sub-agent pattern (consult without handing off) is smart\n• History compression with the Secretary is practical\n• Task-type temperature tuning is thoughtful\n\nThe *core problem* is that routing logic that should be semantic is being done with regex. It'll work 80% of the time and be weirdly wrong the other 20%. That's probably fine for now, but it's technical debt that'll get harder to fix as the system grows.\n\nWant me to dig into any of those specifically?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
