{"status":"success","result":"The highest-leverage fix is one change: *replace the regex classifiers with a model call.*\n\nYou already have `qwen3:4b` (the Secretary) sitting there. It's fast and cheap. Instead of running `selectModel()` and `shouldThink()` through regex, run the incoming message through a structured classification call first:\n\n```\nClassify this message. Return JSON only:\n{\n  \"model\": \"default|coder|analyst|architect|artist\",\n  \"think\": true|false,\n  \"complexity\": \"low|medium|high\"\n}\n\nMessage: \"...\"\n```\n\nThat one change fixes the fragility problem entirely — semantic understanding instead of keyword matching. A 4b model can easily distinguish \"sure, sounds good\" from \"I need to think through this carefully.\"\n\n*For task identification specifically*, go one step further and add `\"task_type\"` to that JSON:\n```\n\"task_type\": \"chat|code|creative|analysis|decision|debug|research\"\n```\n\nThis gives you a richer signal than the current 4-type enum and opens up future routing options without touching core logic.\n\n*For the self-reported escalation problem* — that's harder. A few options ranked by effort:\n\n• *Easy:* Add a confidence field to the classification. If `complexity: \"high\"` upfront, pre-escalate instead of waiting for failure\n• *Medium:* After the model responds, run the output through Secretary with \"did this fully answer the question?\" before sending — catch silent failures\n• *Hard but right:* Track escalation outcomes over time in jarvis.md — which message types needed escalation — and feed that back into the classifier prompt as few-shot examples\n\nThe Secretary-as-classifier approach is probably a 50-line change with high payoff. Want me to sketch out what that code would look like?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
---NANOCLAW_OUTPUT_END---
